8545  // Technically, we should do a signed 32-to-ptr extension here. However,

3022  // when we inline a target in the following, we implicitly assume the
3023  // inlinee instance is the same as the caller's instance.
3024  // Directly jump to the non-inlined slowpath if that's violated.
3025  // Note that for `call_ref` this isn't necessary, because the funcref
3026  // equality check already captures both code and instance equality.
3027  constexpr BranchHint kUnlikelyCrossInstanceCall = BranchHint::kTrue;
3028  // Note that the `implicit_arg` can never be a `WasmImportData`,
3029  // since we don't inline imported functions right now.

3036  InliningTree* tree = feedback_cases[i];
3037  if (!tree || !tree->is_inlined()) {
3038  // Fall through to the next case.
3039  __ Goto(case_blocks[i + 1]);
3040  continue;
3041  }
3042  uint32_t inlined_index = tree->function_index();
3043  // Ensure that we only inline if the inlinee's signature is compatible
3044  // with the call_indirect. In other words, perform the type check that
3045  // would normally be done dynamically (see above
3046  // `BuildIndirectCallTargetAndImplicitArg`) statically on the inlined
3047  // target. This can fail, e.g., because the mapping of feedback back
3048  // to function indices may produce spurious targets, or because the
3049  // feedback in the JS heap has been corrupted by a vulnerability.

3063  is_last_case ? BranchHint::kTrue : BranchHint::kNone;

3065  inline_block, case_blocks[i + 1]);

3072  feedback_slot_, i, inlined_index);

3078  DCHECK_NULL(__ current_block());
3079  }
